column45: The first week of September we experienced tropical storm force winds. Harvest occurred a few days later and several of the plots had no plants standing. Since this had happened after our last stand count, we don't have data for lodged plants.
Sugar beets caused soil compaction on dry side of field, causing dry treatment corn to suffer nutrient deficiency. Kickstarter was applied on June 28 to mitigate the problem
column46: Labor was short during stand count. Stand count spanned over two weeks. As a result, our dry side stand count data (namely, root and stalk lodging) do not as accurately represent the state of the field at harvest as the wet side data
column47: Due to heavy phenotyping (leaf water content and root pulling force) during the week of July 31, we did not take flowering notes on August 1, August 2, and August 3. The dry side was retroactively phenotyped for flowering and silking, but the wet side was not.
column48: Moisture levels were very high at harvest and we were forced to hand harvest 56 plots throughout the field. We dried these samples down in ovens and took all harvest phenotypes at that point.

column45: 05-18-2017. Seed of plot # 140 (rep 2) for the NYH1 experiment is missing. Border seed was planted in its place to fill this gap in the field. Refer to the fieldbook for details of the missig seed.
column46: 07-05-2017. Some plants were accidentally knocked down by the tractor tires when the field was side-dressed. This happened because the plants were too tall. Plants were recounted to account for this plot damage.
column47: 08-26-2017. Some plots were damaged by mammals (raccoons). Plants were recounted and yield data discarded if mammal damage was significant.
column48: 2017-12-08. We got new probes to measure soil temperature and soil moisture, but we didn't get any data from those measurements. We suspect there's an issue with the weather station. It would be helpful to check/fix it.
